lenders.name: VW Repair Phoenix
lenders.occupational_info:
Volkswagen, or VW, is a German car manufacturer which is headquartered in Wolfsburg, Germany. It was established in 1937, and is the top-selling marque of the Volkswagen Group, VW being the second-largest car maker in the world. 

In the top 10 list of the best-selling cars of all time, VW has three cars: The Golf, the Beetle, and the Passat. VW also has the most cars from any car manufacturer which are still being manufactured on this list.

The German name Volkswagen translates to the English “People’s Automobile.” 


The People's Car project from 1932–1938

During the early part of the 1930s, the auto industry in Germany was mainly comprised of high-end models, where, the average German was unable to afford anything more than a motorcycle. Because of this, only one German from 50 was able to own a car. 

A number of car makers began to seek new markets and thus began the “Peoples’ Car” projects, which included the Adler AutoBahn, the Mercedes 170H, the Hanomag 1.3L, and the Steyr 55.

A well-known designer of high-end autos and race cars – Ferdinand Porsche – had tried over the previous number of years to entice manufacturers to generate an interest in a smaller car that was far more suitable to the average German family. At the time, he considered the smaller cars were simply big cars that were stripped down to the basics. 

In 1933, he designed and manufactured a car called “Volksauto,” which used many of the concepts that were freely available at that time, together with a number of his own. He put together a car that came with torsion bar suspension, an air-cooled rear engine, and a shape like a beetle, whereby the front hood was rounded to offer superior aerodynamics, which was a necessity given that the engine was particularly small. 

In 1932, when many of the projects were still in early development, Adolf Hitler became involved. He ordered that a basic vehicle be produced that was capable of carrying no less than two adults, with three children in the rear, at a speed of up to 62 mph (100 km/h). It was Hitler’s desire to permit his German citizens to have as much access to German cars as the American people had to their cars.

Thus, the “People’s Car” was to be made available to Third Reich citizens which was priced at 990 Reichsmark (the equivalent of US$396) - a similar price to that of a small motorcycle. The car could be purchased through a monthly savings plan. 

In spite of heavy lobbying very much in favor of the plan, it became apparent that it was an impossible feat for private industry to build a car for a mere 990RM. Given the grave scenario, Hitler took it upon himself to sponsor a state-owned factory which would use the design by Ferdinand Porsche. 

The concept was that the ordinary German would purchase the car through a savings scheme. Nevertheless, the entire scheme proved unsound, and it was only down to the lack of accountability and corruption of the Nazi regime that it actually became possible. 


For a superior VW repair specialist, look no further than Volkswagen Repair Services in Phoenix, AZ.
